{"key":"processedPost-13477780","value":{"id":13477780,"first":13465668,"last":13477971,"when":1289669090,"utime":"11/13/10 07:24 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />sigh... ok so noone on here has bought or made a flowhood that they had to \"put together\"?<br /></blockquote><br /><br /><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/shocked.gif\" alt=\":shocked:\" title=\":shocked:\"/><br /><br />There's been hundreds of good flowhood threads.&nbsp; In the top of every page, you'll see a 'search posts' link where you'll find everything you're asking.<br /><br />In short, install the motor.&nbsp; Use caulk or weather stripping to get a good seal between the motor flange and the flowhood cabinet.&nbsp; Hook the motor up to one speed, and I suggest starting off with 'low'.&nbsp; Tape off the rest of the wires as shown on the wiring diagram.<br /><br />Run the motor and test flow.&nbsp; If it doesn't bend a Bic lighter flame over 60 degrees when placed six inches from the filter face, step up to the next speed.&nbsp; Do this until you have the right speed and then seal every thing up.&nbsp; There's no reason for a switch.<br /><br />If for some reason you 'want' a speed switch, make sure it's motor rated, not general purpose, regardless of the amps/volts rating.&nbsp; However, I suggest wiring for the correct speed and being done with it.&nbsp; Don't forget to use a really good prefilter.<br /><br />Start it up and run it in a tightly closed small room for at least an hour before you start sterile work.&nbsp; Don't leave it running all the time.<br />RR","title":"Re: New Flowhood! need help. Series IV"}}